  <main>
    <div class="stk-wrap">

      <!-- ── HEADER ── -->
      <header class="stk-head">
        <span class="stk-eyebrow">The Stack</span>
        <h1 class="stk-h1">The library and the <em>projection room.</em></h1>
        <p class="stk-lead">What I'm reading and what I've watched — pulled from <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/user/show/131128315-harsh-arya" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Goodreads</a> and <a href="https://www.imdb.com/user/p.zu2d65dgnmfcpzmntmp45p2wbm/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">IMDb</a>. I use the IMDb watchlist backwards — it's a record of what I've already seen.</p>
        <p class="stk-stamp">Updated weekly · Mondays</p>

        <div class="stk-stats">
          <div><div class="stk-stat-n">118</div><div class="stk-stat-l">books read · since 2021</div></div>
          <div><div class="stk-stat-n">624</div><div class="stk-stat-l">films logged · since 2020</div></div>
          <div><div class="stk-stat-n">3</div><div class="stk-stat-l">open right now</div></div>
        </div>
      </header>

      <!-- ── CURRENTLY READING ── -->
      <section class="stk-sec">
        <div class="stk-kicker">On the side table</div>
        <h2 class="stk-h2">Currently <em>reading.</em></h2>
        <p class="stk-note">Three open at once. The Saunders is the morning book, the Murakami sits by the kettle, the Piyush Mishra travels. Tap a spine.</p>

        <div class="reading-row" id="readingRow">
          <button class="rspine rspine--a" type="button" data-card="rc-vigil">
            <span class="rs-text">Vigil</span><span class="rs-auth">Saunders</span>
          </button>
          <button class="rspine rspine--b" type="button" data-card="rc-birthday">
            <span class="rs-text">Birthday Stories</span><span class="rs-auth">ed. Murakami</span>
          </button>
          <button class="rspine rspine--c" type="button" data-card="rc-piyush">
            <span class="rs-text">Tumhari Auqaat Kya Hai</span><span class="rs-auth">Mishra</span>
          </button>
          <!-- the book that isn't on the shelf -->
          <a class="rspine rspine--gap" href="/speakeasy/" aria-label="A book that isn't on the shelf"></a>
        </div>

        <div class="reading-card" id="rc-vigil">
          <div class="rc-eyebrow">Picked up Apr 2026 · a chapter a morning</div>
          <div class="rc-title">Vigil</div>
          <div class="rc-auth">George Saunders</div>
          <div class="rc-note">Saunders writes the way I want to think when I'm tired — patient, generous, willing to look at the same small thing twice.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="reading-card" id="rc-birthday">
          <div class="rc-eyebrow">15% in</div>
          <div class="rc-title">Birthday Stories</div>
          <div class="rc-auth">Selected &amp; introduced by Haruki Murakami</div>
          <div class="rc-note">An anthology of birthday stories, picked by Murakami. The introductions are better than half the stories — which is its own kind of treat.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="reading-card" id="rc-piyush">
          <div class="rc-eyebrow">24% in</div>
          <div class="rc-title">Tumhari Auqaat Kya Hai</div>
          <div class="rc-auth">Piyush Mishra</div>
          <div class="rc-note">The Hindi I should have grown up reading more of. Half memoir, half manifesto, half poetry — yes, three halves, that's how it works.</div>
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- ── BOOKS I PRESS ON PEOPLE ── -->
      <section class="stk-sec">
        <div class="stk-kicker">Five stars · handed to friends</div>
        <h2 class="stk-h2">Books I <em>press on people.</em></h2>
        <p class="stk-note">Books I've physically given away, or texted someone to buy. R. K. Narayan dominates this row — that isn't an accident. Tap a cover for why.</p>

        <div class="pbook-grid">
          <button class="pbook pbook--o" type="button">
            <span class="p-num">I</span>
            <span class="p-title">Tuesdays with Morrie</span>
            <span class="p-auth">Mitch Albom</span>
            <span class="p-note"><span class="p-note-meta">Hand to · anyone drifting</span>For when someone needs reminding that paying attention is the only practice that matters.</span>
          </button>
          <button class="pbook" type="button">
            <span class="p-num">II</span>
            <span class="p-title">Malgudi Days</span>
            <span class="p-auth">R. K. Narayan</span>
            <span class="p-note"><span class="p-note-meta">Hand to · everyone</span>The reason I think of small towns the way I do. The reason Ratlam is a story in my head, not an embarrassment.</span>
          </button>
          <button class="pbook" type="button">
            <span class="p-num">III</span>
            <span class="p-title">The English Teacher</span>
            <span class="p-auth">R. K. Narayan</span>
            <span class="p-note"><span class="p-note-meta">Hand to · grieving friends</span>Loss without melodrama. The book I bring up when someone is trying to write about losing a parent.</span>
          </button>
          <button class="pbook" type="button">
            <span class="p-num">IV</span>
            <span class="p-title">The Financial Expert</span>
            <span class="p-auth">R. K. Narayan</span>
            <span class="p-note"><span class="p-note-meta">Hand to · operators</span>What ambition looks like in a small place. Funny on the surface, brutal underneath.</span>
          </button>
          <button class="pbook" type="button">
            <span class="p-num">V</span>
            <span class="p-title">Talkative Man</span>
            <span class="p-auth">R. K. Narayan</span>
            <span class="p-note"><span class="p-note-meta">Hand to · writers</span>Slim, sharp, almost a sketch — but the voice is the point.</span>
          </button>
          <button class="pbook" type="button">
            <span class="p-num">VI</span>
            <span class="p-title">Piccadilly Jim</span>
            <span class="p-auth">P. G. Wodehouse</span>
            <span class="p-note"><span class="p-note-meta">Hand to · anyone in a bad mood</span>Comfort in book form. Comedy that's actually well-built underneath.</span>
          </button>
          <button class="pbook" type="button">
            <span class="p-num">VII</span>
            <span class="p-title">Five Point Someone</span>
            <span class="p-auth">Chetan Bhagat</span>
            <span class="p-note"><span class="p-note-meta">Hand to · 17-year-olds</span>Yes, this one. Right book, right age. Doesn't have to be Tolstoy to land.</span>
          </button>
          <button class="pbook" type="button">
            <span class="p-num">VIII</span>
            <span class="p-title">Mind-Blowing Experiments</span>
            <span class="p-auth">Mike Goldsmith</span>
            <span class="p-note"><span class="p-note-meta">Hand to · curious kids</span>The book that made me think being a scientist was a way of being playful as a job.</span>
          </button>
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- ── SCREENING ROOM ── -->
      <section class="stk-sec">
        <div class="stk-kicker">The projection room</div>
        <h2 class="stk-h2">Films I'd <em>defend at dinner.</em></h2>
        <p class="stk-note">The 10/10 list is short on purpose — the films I'd rewatch on a flight, on a Sunday, on a hard day. Tap a title to put it on the screen.</p>

        <div class="screen" id="screen">
          <div class="screen-now">Now showing</div>
          <div>
            <h3 class="screen-film" id="screenFilm">Perfect Days</h3>
            <p class="screen-meta" id="screenMeta">Wim Wenders · 2023 · Japan <strong>Rated 10</strong></p>
            <p class="screen-q" id="screenQ">Hirayama cleans Tokyo's toilets, listens to cassettes, photographs trees. A film about how small attention compounds.</p>
          </div>
